Introduction¶

This document explores a dataset containing FordGo journey information from the year 2018.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Although this project focusses on communication of data findings, wrangling had to be first be performed to ensure the dataset was tidy for analysis and findings were accurate.

# Getting the data, extracting zip files and storing in folder
for month in range(1, 13):
    month_string = str(month)
    month_leading_zero = month_string.zfill(2)
    print(month_leading_zero)
    bike_data_url_2018 = 'https://s3.amazonaws.com/fordgobike-data/2018' + month_leading_zero + \
    '-fordgobike-tripdata.csv.zip'
    response_2018 = requests.get(bike_data_url_2018)
    ## Extract zip file;
    unzipped_files_2018 = zipfile.ZipFile(io.BytesIO(response_2018.content))
    unzipped_files_2018.extractall('2018-fordgobike-tripdata')

Quality¶

  • Missing data - there are null values in a number of different columns

  • Erroneous datatypes ('start_time' and 'end_time' should be datetime data type, 'member_birth_year' should be changed to an integer datatype, 'user_type' and 'member_gender' could be changed to a category datatype, 'bike_share_for_all_trip' could also be changed to a boolean datatype, 'bike_id', 'start_station_id' and 'end_station_id' should be changed to strings)

  • The minimum birth year is shown as 1881 - there are a number of member_birth_years that indicate people are over 70 years old which seems extremely unlikely that they would be riding bikes

Note of Possible Additions/Changes which can be made during exploration¶

  • Duration in minutes column could be added which is easier to comprehend for communicating findings

  • Can make a month column to investigate the effect of time of year

  • Distance could be considered but this would be as the crow flies and not necessarily the route taken by the rider

Erroneous datatypes ('start_time' and 'end_time' should be datetime data type, 'member_birth_year' should be changed to an integer datatype, 'user_type' and 'member_gender' could be changed to a category datatype, 'bike_share_for_all_trip' could also be changed to a category datatype, 'bike_id', 'start_station_id' and 'end_station_id' should be changed to strings)¶
Define¶

Change the datatypes as follows:

  • 'start_time' and 'end_time' to be converted to datetime data type
  • 'member_birth_year' to be converted to an integer datatype
  • 'bike_id', 'start_station_id' and 'end_station_id' to be converted to string, i.e. object datatype since no numerical calculations should be performed
  • 'user_type' and 'member_gender' to be converted to a category datatype
  • 'bike_share_for_all_trip' to be converted to a a category datatype

Data Exploration¶

Structure of the Dataset¶

After cleaning the data, there are 1,725,138 rows in the dataset with 15 features (duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip). The variables are a mixture of datetimes, integers, floats, strings and categories. The categories for user_type are “Subscriber” = Member or “Customer” = Casual. The categories for gender are Female, Male or Other. A bike_share_for_all_trip variable indicates whether the rider is part of the Bike Share For All program available for those on a low income.

Main Features of the Dataset¶

It is of interest to find out which features are best for predicting the duration and also the features affecting frequency of bike trips.

Features to Support Investigation¶

It is expected that time of day and day of the week will have the strongest effect on both the frequency and duration of the bike ride, with longer and more frequent bike rides during the commuting hours. Additionally it is expected that time of year as well as user type, that is whether the rider is a subscriber or customer, and member birth year may affect the frequency and duration of trips. Gender will also be investigated to understand if this effects the frequency and duration of bike rides.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section distributions of individual variables will be investigated.

# calculating the distance travelled during the bike trip
import numpy as np
def haversine_np(start_station_longitude, start_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, end_station_latitude):
    """
    Calculate the great circle distance between two points
    on the earth (specified in decimal degrees)
    All args must be of equal length.    
    """
    start_station_longitude, start_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, end_station_latitude = map(np.radians, [start_station_longitude, start_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, end_station_latitude])
    dlon = end_station_longitude - start_station_longitude
    dlat = end_station_latitude - start_station_latitude
    a = np.sin(dlat/2.0)**2 + np.cos(start_station_latitude) * np.cos(end_station_latitude) * np.sin(dlon/2.0)**2
    c = 2 * np.arcsin(np.sqrt(a))
    km = 6367 * c
    return km

Univariate Exploration Conclusions¶

The duration of bike trips was highly skewed to the right therefore a log scale was used instead to give a log normal distribution. The duration of bike trips in minutes was added to the data so it was easier to comprehend. It is clear from the graph produced that the majority of bike rides are under 30 minutes with the average time being around the 9-10 minute mark.

Additionally, time of day and day of the week was investigated and suggested the bikes were being used for commuting to work since the most popular times were from 07:00-09:00 and 16:00-19:00 on weekdays. A month column was also added to give insight into the frequency of bike trips by each month of the year. It was evident that as expected there were more bike trips taken during the warmer months from May - October.

An age column was added to determine the age of the members in the year 2018 when this data was gathered. The graph illustrated a peak of riders around 30 years old. The data was cleaned to remove those over the age of 65 which was done by removing the top 1% of the dataset.

It was found there were more subscribers than customers taking bike trips. Furthermore, more males took bike trips compared to those registered as female or other. The majority of trips were not part of the bike share for all trip scheme.

Moreover, the longitude and latitude columns were used to create a distance column to indicate the distance travelled during the trip. The majority of bike trips were under 2km.

Bivariate Exploration Conclusions¶

Features of Interest¶

During this part of the investigation it was found that on average those who identified as female or other as their gender took longer bike rides than males. Additionally, customers took longer bike rides than those who were members. Those not involved in the bike share for all scheme took longer bike trips. Time of year didn't significantly affect duration of bike trip, however it did show a slight increase in the warmer summer months. The day of the week had an effect on trip duration with longer bike rides taking place at the weekend. In addition longer bike trips took place between the hours of 2-3pm.

Interestingly more trips are taken at the beginning of the year by members who are slightly older. With regards to day of the week, more younger people took bike trips at the weekend. Trips taken during very late at night and into the hours of the very early morning were taken by younger people.

When considering demographics from this clustered bar chart it is evident that subscribers took more bike rides than customers and the majority of both subscribers and customers were male.

Other Features¶

When considering other features in the dataset, from the above exploration it is evident that those who identified as female or other travelled a slightly greater distance than males and customers travelled further than subscribers on average, however this was very slight. Those who were not in the bike share for all scheme also travelled a slightly longer distance than those who were involved in the scheme. When considering the demographics of the members it is clear that most members are in their early 30s. Moreover, those involved in the bike share for all scheme are on average younger than those who aren't involved.

Moving forward, 'age', 'distance' and 'bike share for all' won't be used in any further analysis as these are not related to the features of interest and don't show strong relationships with other features in the dataset.

Multivariate Exploration Conclusions¶

The investigation of bike trip length and frequency was extended by looking at the impact of day of week and time of day. The multivariate exploration highlighted that time of day and day of the week had an effect on the frequency of bike trips taken with most taken during weekdays and commuting hours as people were using the bike to travel to work.

As expected more bike trips indeed occurred during commuting hours however, and that longer bike trips on average occurred during the weekends compared to the weekdays. However, it was surprising that during weekdays some of the longest duration of bike trips took place between 1am-3am.

It was found that all genders took longer bike rides at the weekends and those identifying as 'female' or 'other' took longer bike trips on all days. Moreover, customers took longer trips than subscribers on all days of the week.

Conclusions¶

In the exploration, I found that most bike trips lasted under 30 minutes with the average lasting around approximately 9 minutes. It was also found that most trips were under 2km. I found that most users of Ford GoBikes used the bikes between typical commuting hours and on weekdays suggesting that a number of cyclists were using the bikes to travel to work. Additionally, it was found that frequency would increase during the warmer months of the year and would be less during the colder winter months.

It was found that most users of the service are subscribers compared to a rather small proportion who were customers, although it was interesting to find that when customers do use the bikes then they take longer bike trips than subscribers do on average.

When considering how demographics affects bike trip frequency and duration it was found that the service was most popular with those in their mid twenties to mid thirties and number of users decreased after the age of thirty for every increase in year of age. Additionally it was found that males were more likely to use the service however it was interesting that when females or those who selected 'other' as their gender took bike trips then these lasted longer than those taken by males. In addition it was found that the majority of bike trips were not part of the Bike Share for All Scheme.

When conducting a bivariate exploration of the data, it was clear there were not strong correlations between the numeric variables in the dataset i.e age, duration, distance. However, several insights into the relationships with categorical variables were found. As aforementioned, females and those identified as 'other' took longer bike trips than males and customers took longer trips than subscribers. There was no strong relationship found between duration of trip and if a participant was involved in the bike share for all scheme. It was found that the month of the year didn't have a strong effect on the duration of the bike trip, however the day of the week was related with longer trips happening during the weekends. Time of day also affected the length of the trip with longer trips during the afternoon.

When conducting the univariate exploration it was confirmed that most bike trips were taken during the week between the most popular commuting hours. Additionally it was found that longer bike trips occurred during the weekend on average and it was surprising to find that during the weekdays the longest bike trips occurred from 1am - 3am.

Outside of the main variables of interest it was found that females and those who selected 'other' as their gender travelled a greater distance, as did customers as opposed to subscribers, and those not involved in the bike share for all also travelled a greater distance. From the above it is clear that month or day of the week doesn't affect distance travelled however it is evident that a greater distance was travelled in the mornings, especially from 7am-8am. When investigating age most members were in their early 30s regardless of gender or user type. Interestingly, those involved in the bike share for all scheme are on average younger than those who aren't involved which is possibly as it is for low income members and it's possible these are younger on average. Younger people took bike trips at the weekend. Trips taken during very late at night and into the hours of the very early morning were taken by younger people on average.
